            "author_info": {
                "name": "John Miller",
                "href": "/profile/John-Miller-301"
            },
            "answer_text": "We used Mathematical Methods in the Physical Sciences, by Mary Boas.  I like Boas's writing style, and she takes things at a pace that's easy to follow for self-study.  Ten years out of college and I still thumb through it now and then.  It's the assigned undergrad textbook at the university where I work now. I've seen other folks use Advanced Engineering Mathematics by Erwin Kreysig, and for grad students, Arfken's  Mathematical Methods for Physicists gets uses a lot. If you're an undergrad, pick up a copy of each from the library and see which you like better.  You can always pick up older versions cheaply, too: the content doesn't change much between them. I'd be interested to hear what you end up with! ",
